<HEAD>Jupiter-Bound Galileo Spacecraft Fires Thrusters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Galileo spacecraft, looping through
the solar system on the way to its 1995 exploration of Jupiter,
fired its thrusters today in a major maneuver meant to steer it
near Earth late this year.
   ``We're trying to reshape the trajectory slightly so we move
closer and closer to our aim point near Earth on Dec. 8,'' said
Neal Ausman, mission director at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
   Galileo's tiny rocket thrusters, which are small enough to fit
in the palm of a hand, started firing at 11:10 a.m. PDT and will
fire roughly 3,000 times by the time the maneuver ends Saturday
afternoon, laboratory spokesman Jim Wilson said.
   The two-day maneuver will slow the spacecraft, which was
traveling about 66,000 mph earlier today, by about 25 mph. It also
will gradually alter its direction, Ausman said.
   It is the second of three or four maneuvers needed to bring
Galileo within 1,000 miles of Earth, which will act as a gravity
slingshot to help expand the spacecraft's orbit around the sun and
propel it toward Jupiter, he added. Without maneuvers, the
spacecraft would miss Earth by 1.5 million miles.
   As of today, Galileo was 96 million miles from Earth, but has
traveled a looping path of 365 million miles since it was launched
from space shuttle Atlantis last Oct. 18. Its trip to Jupiter will
total 2.4 billion miles.
   Galileo will make a second swing past Earth in December 1992. It
flew past Venus in another gravity slingshot maneuver on Feb. 9.
   In July 1995, the spacecraft separates into a 4,890-pound
orbiter and a 760-pound probe. They are scheduled to reach Jupiter,
the solar system's largest planet, on Dec. 7, 1995.
   The probe will plunge into the planet's atmosphere, relaying
measurements to the orbiter before the probe is destroyed by
intense atmospheric pressure. The orbiter will spend at least two
years studying and taking snapshots of Jupiter and its major moons
Europa, Ganymede and Callisto.
</TEXT>
