<HEAD>With Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Flyby Allows Photos of Moon's Far Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists say pictures of the far side
of the moon taken by the spacecraft Galileo will help fill a blank
spot on the map of the planet.
   The pictures, taken as Galileo sped past the moon and Earth on
its six-year voyage to Jupiter, also should reveal more about the
mineral content of the moon's crust, scientists said Monday.
   ``We're actually doing some new observation,'' said James Head,
a member of Galileo's imaging team at NASA's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration displayed
black and white photos of the full moon that provided a sharp image
of the Orientale Basin as well as portions of both the near and far
sides of the moon.
   The spacecraft swung into the Earth's gravitational field
Saturday, hurtling 597 miles above the western Atlantic at the
point of its closest approach.
   By sweeping near Earth, Galileo was able to use gravitational
pull like a slingshot to increase its speed by 11,600 mph, boosting
its velocity to 79,000 mph in relation to the sun.
   Galileo's approach allowed scientists to focus the craft's
cameras on the far side of the moon for the first exploration of
the region since NASA's Apollo missions in the 1970s.
   The cameras photographed a wedge of moonscape near the south
pole on the far side that somehow was missed by previous U.S. and
Soviet mapping missions, said project scientist Torrence Johnson.
   ``That's interesting, it's got craters just like the rest of the
moon, but there's no great scientific surprise in that,'' Johnson
said.
   A subsequent journey through the Earth's magnetic field gave
scientists their first measurements of a solar storm in which
magnetically charged ions take on higher energy levels.
   The data could reveal whether the majority of these ions, which
trigger colorful auroras near Earth's magnetic poles, come from the
sun or Earth, said Lou Frank, chairman of Galileo's magnetic field
working group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

