<HEAD>Thrusters Fire as Galileo Starts First Trajectory Change on Jupiter
Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three weeks after its launch from a
shuttle, the Galileo spacecraft fired its thrusters Thursday to
begin the first of about 30 course changes needed for its
roundabout six-year trip to Jupiter.
   ``We've started the first trajectory correction maneuver,''
mission director Neal Ausman said after the three-day series of
thruster ignitions got under way at 8:31 a.m. PST.
   During the maneuver, Galileo is firing four of its 12 thrusters
in a series of pulses, he said. No individual pulse exceeds two
minutes, each set of pulses takes about 45 minutes, and the entire
maneuver will be completed Saturday night.
   Two other thrusters may be used to correct the spacecraft's rate
of spin and the direction toward which it points, said Ausman, of
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory.
   The trajectory change is meant to aim Galileo for its flight
past Venus in February. The spacecraft, launched from space shuttle
Atlantis on Oct. 18, will swoop by Venus once and Earth twice so
the planets can act as ``gravity slingshots'' to propel Galileo
toward Jupiter during the $1.9 billion mission.
   On Thursday, Galileo was about 31 million miles into its looping
2.4 billion-mile journey to the solar system's largest planet,
Ausman said. It was about 4.6 million miles from Earth and 58.5
million miles from Venus, traveling at 60,376 mph relative to the
sun.
   In July 1995, Galileo will separate into an orbiter and a probe.
The orbiter will circle Jupiter for 22 months starting in December
1995, the same month the probe will parachute into the Jovian
atmosphere, making measurements for 75 minutes until it is crushed
by intense pressure.
   About 30 course corrections involving thruster firings spread
over 135 days will be required en route to Jupiter, Ausman said.
   Galileo has ignited its 3.5 inch-long thrusters on other
occasions, but those firings were to adjust spin or direction,
Ausman said. The three-day maneuver that started Thursday is
Galileo's first trajectory correction, he added.
   Ausman said the West German-built thrusters have to fire in
pulses to avoid contaminating sensitive parts of Galileo. The
thrusters are attached to the spinning part of Galileo, and can
fire only when they are not above sensitive areas on the
non-spinning section of the spacecraft.
   The thrusters also are fired in pulses because NASA fears
continuous firing might make them overheat and burn through, a
problem that developed on the same type of thrusters on two
satellites in recent years, Ausman said.
</TEXT>
