<HEAD>Galileo Probe Rebuilt For October Launch, 1995 Plunge Into Jovian
Skies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A space probe grounded for 3{ years by
the Challenger explosion has been rebuilt for an October launch to
Jupiter, where it will plunge to its doom as it seeks clues to the
birth of the solar system.
   The $1.36 billion Galileo mission should climax in December 1995,
when the probe deploys a parachute and collects information for 75
minutes before it is crushed by Jupiter's intense atmospheric
pressure.
   Its mother ship, the Galileo orbiter, will circle the planet for
22 months.
   Hughes Aircraft Co. planned to deliver the refurbished $157
million Galileo probe late this afternoon in Pasadena, where NASA's
Jet Propulsion Laboratory is completing modifications to the orbiter.
   ``This is a very proud day for us. We are ready to deliver it to
JPL on its way to Jupiter,'' Hughes Vice President Steven Dorfman
said at a news conference Tuesday.
   JPL will send the 4-foot-diameter, teardrop-shaped probe to
Kennedy Space Center in Florida in late April, followed by the
orbiter in mid-May. The probe and orbiter then will be hooked up
together, placed atop a booster rocket, and finally loaded into the
cargo bay of the shuttle Atlantis.
   The shuttle, set for launch no earlier than Oct. 12 and no later
than about Nov. 21, will release the combined Galileo spacecraft
into Earth orbit. Then Galileo's rocket will fire, sending the
orbiter and probe on a circuitous, 2.4-billion-mile, six-year voyage
to the solar system's largest planet, which is the fifth planet from
the sun and is about 400 million miles from Earth.
   En route to the giant gaseous planet, Galileo will observe two
asteroids. The probe and orbiter will separate 150 days before they
reach Jupiter, then fly in tandem until the probe enters the
atmosphere at 115,000 mph. The probe will deploy a parachute and
descend about 370 miles through Jovian skies until it is crushed by
pressure more than 25 times Earth's atmosphere.
   Data from the probe will help scientists better understand the
origin of Jupiter, the solar system and the universe, said Richard
Young, Galileo probe project scientist at the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration's Ames Research Center in Mountain View.
   Scientists believe the Jovian atmosphere could be a sample of the
original material from which stars are formed, according to a Hughes
statement.
   The orbiter will measure Jupiter's electrical particle and
magnetic fields, and snap 50,000 photographs of the planet and its
moons, including Io, Europa, Ganymede and Callisto, which were
discovered in 1610 by Italian astronomer Galileo Galilei.
   The spacecraft had been scheduled for launch from a space shuttle
in May 1986 and powered out of orbit atop a Centaur booster for a
three-year trip to Jupiter. But Challenger exploded on Jan. 28,
1986, killing its crew of seven and grounding the shuttle fleet
until last fall.
   After the tragedy, NASA decided it was too dangerous to carry
liquid-fueled Centaur rockets aboard the shuttle. Galileo's route to
Jupiter was drastically redesigned and lengthened from three years
to six because Earth and Jupiter are no longer aligned as ideally as
they were in 1986 and because Galileo's new solid-fueled booster is
less powerful.
   The launch delay and longer flight time prompted a decision to
take the probe apart for refurbishing and to make sure some parts
wouldn't fail because of aging.
   White House approval for the launch is expected in September,
said Richard Spehalski, Galileo project manager at JPL. Such
approval is needed because the probe and orbiter each carry a power
plant and heater containing radioactive plutonium. A NASA
environmental impact statement concluded last month that the risk of
a nuclear accident when the shuttle lifts off with Galileo is very
small.
</TEXT>
